#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:5
msgid "Scrapy at a glance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:7
msgid ""
"Scrapy is an application framework for crawling web sites and extracting "
"structured data which can be used for a wide range of useful applications, "
"like data mining, information processing or historical archival."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:11
msgid ""
"Even though Scrapy was originally designed for `screen scraping`_ (more "
"precisely, `web scraping`_), it can also be used to extract data using APIs "
"(such as `Amazon Associates Web Services`_) or as a general purpose web "
"crawler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:16
msgid ""
"The purpose of this document is to introduce you to the concepts behind "
"Scrapy so you can get an idea of how it works and decide if Scrapy is what "
"you need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:19
msgid ""
"When you're ready to start a project, you can :ref:`start with the tutorial "
"<intro-tutorial>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:23
msgid "Pick a website"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:25
msgid ""
"So you need to extract some information from a website, but the website "
"doesn't provide any API or mechanism to access that info programmatically.  "
"Scrapy can help you extract that information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:29
msgid ""
"Let's say we want to extract the URL, name, description and size of all "
"torrent files added today in the `Mininova`_ site."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:32
msgid "The list of all torrents added today can be found on this page:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:34
msgid "http://www.mininova.org/today"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:39
msgid "Define the data you want to scrape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:41
msgid ""
"The first thing is to define the data we want to scrape. In Scrapy, this is "
"done through :ref:`Scrapy Items <topics-items>` (Torrent files, in this "
"case)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:44
msgid "This would be our Item::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:46
msgid ""
"import scrapy\n"
"\n"
"class TorrentItem(scrapy.Item):\n"
"    url = scrapy.Field()\n"
"    name = scrapy.Field()\n"
"    description = scrapy.Field()\n"
"    size = scrapy.Field()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:55
msgid "Write a Spider to extract the data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:57
msgid ""
"The next thing is to write a Spider which defines the start URL (http://www."
"mininova.org/today), the rules for following links and the rules for "
"extracting the data from pages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:61
msgid ""
"If we take a look at that page content we'll see that all torrent URLs are "
"like ``http://www.mininova.org/tor/NUMBER`` where ``NUMBER`` is an integer. "
"We'll use that to construct the regular expression for the links to follow: "
"``/tor/\\d+``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:65
msgid ""
"We'll use `XPath`_ for selecting the data to extract from the web page HTML "
"source. Let's take one of those torrent pages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:68
msgid "http://www.mininova.org/tor/2676093"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:70
msgid ""
"And look at the page HTML source to construct the XPath to select the data "
"we want which is: torrent name, description and size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:75
msgid ""
"By looking at the page HTML source we can see that the file name is "
"contained inside a ``<h1>`` tag::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:78
msgid "<h1>Darwin - The Evolution Of An Exhibition</h1>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:82
msgid "An XPath expression to extract the name could be::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:84
msgid "//h1/text()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:88
msgid ""
"And the description is contained inside a ``<div>`` tag with "
"``id=\"description\"``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:90
msgid ""
"<h2>Description:</h2>\n"
"\n"
"<div id=\"description\">\n"
"Short documentary made for Plymouth City Museum and Art Gallery regarding "
"the setup of an exhibit about Charles Darwin in conjunction with the 200th "
"anniversary of his birth.\n"
"\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:99
msgid "An XPath expression to select the description could be::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:101
msgid "//div[@id='description']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:105
msgid ""
"Finally, the file size is contained in the second ``<p>`` tag inside the "
"``<div>`` tag with ``id=specifications``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:108
msgid ""
"<div id=\"specifications\">\n"
"\n"
"<p>\n"
"<strong>Category:</strong>\n"
"<a href=\"/cat/4\">Movies</a> &gt; <a href=\"/sub/35\">Documentary</a>\n"
"</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>\n"
"<strong>Total size:</strong>\n"
"150.62&nbsp;megabyte</p>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:122
msgid "An XPath expression to select the file size could be::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:124
msgid "//div[@id='specifications']/p[2]/text()[2]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:128
msgid "For more information about XPath see the `XPath reference`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:130
msgid "Finally, here's the spider code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:132
msgid ""
"from scrapy.contrib.spiders import CrawlSpider, Rule\n"
"from scrapy.contrib.linkextractors import LinkExtractor\n"
"\n"
"class MininovaSpider(CrawlSpider):\n"
"\n"
"    name = 'mininova'\n"
"    allowed_domains = ['mininova.org']\n"
"    start_urls = ['http://www.mininova.org/today']\n"
"    rules = [Rule(LinkExtractor(allow=['/tor/\\d+']), 'parse_torrent')]\n"
"\n"
"    def parse_torrent(self, response):\n"
"        torrent = TorrentItem()\n"
"        torrent['url'] = response.url\n"
"        torrent['name'] = response.xpath(\"//h1/text()\").extract()\n"
"        torrent['description'] = response.xpath(\"//"
"div[@id='description']\").extract()\n"
"        torrent['size'] = response.xpath(\"//div[@id='info-left']/p[2]/text()"
"[2]\").extract()\n"
"        return torrent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:150
msgid ""
"The ``TorrentItem`` class is :ref:`defined above <intro-overview-item>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:153
msgid "Run the spider to extract the data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:155
msgid ""
"Finally, we'll run the spider to crawl the site and output the file "
"``scraped_data.json`` with the scraped data in JSON format::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:158
msgid "scrapy crawl mininova -o scraped_data.json"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:160
msgid ""
"This uses :ref:`feed exports <topics-feed-exports>` to generate the JSON "
"file. You can easily change the export format (XML or CSV, for example) or "
"the storage backend (FTP or `Amazon S3`_, for example)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:164
msgid ""
"You can also write an :ref:`item pipeline <topics-item-pipeline>` to store "
"the items in a database very easily."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:168
msgid "Review scraped data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:170
msgid ""
"If you check the ``scraped_data.json`` file after the process finishes, "
"you'll see the scraped items there::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:173
msgid ""
"[{\"url\": \"http://www.mininova.org/tor/2676093\", \"name\": [\"Darwin - "
"The Evolution Of An Exhibition\"], \"description\": [\"Short documentary "
"made for Plymouth ...\"], \"size\": [\"150.62 megabyte\"]},\n"
"# ... other items ...\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:177
msgid ""
"You'll notice that all field values (except for the ``url`` which was "
"assigned directly) are actually lists. This is because the :ref:`selectors "
"<topics-selectors>` return lists. You may want to store single values, or "
"perform some additional parsing/cleansing to the values. That's what :ref:"
"`Item Loaders <topics-loaders>` are for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:186
msgid "What else?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:188
msgid ""
"You've seen how to extract and store items from a website using Scrapy, but "
"this is just the surface. Scrapy provides a lot of powerful features for "
"making scraping easy and efficient, such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:192
msgid ""
"Built-in support for :ref:`selecting and extracting <topics-selectors>` data "
"from HTML and XML sources"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:195
msgid ""
"Built-in support for cleaning and sanitizing the scraped data using a "
"collection of reusable filters (called :ref:`Item Loaders <topics-loaders>`) "
"shared between all the spiders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:199
msgid ""
"Built-in support for :ref:`generating feed exports <topics-feed-exports>` in "
"multiple formats (JSON, CSV, XML) and storing them in multiple backends "
"(FTP, S3, local filesystem)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:203
msgid ""
"A media pipeline for :ref:`automatically downloading images <topics-images>` "
"(or any other media) associated with the scraped items"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:206
msgid ""
"Support for :ref:`extending Scrapy <extending-scrapy>` by plugging your own "
"functionality using :ref:`signals <topics-signals>` and a well-defined API "
"(middlewares, :ref:`extensions <topics-extensions>`, and :ref:`pipelines "
"<topics-item-pipeline>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:211
msgid "Wide range of built-in middlewares and extensions for:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:213
msgid "cookies and session handling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:214
msgid "HTTP compression"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:215
msgid "HTTP authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:216
msgid "HTTP cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:217
msgid "user-agent spoofing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:218
msgid "robots.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:219
msgid "crawl depth restriction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:220
msgid "and more"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:222
msgid ""
"Robust encoding support and auto-detection, for dealing with foreign, non-"
"standard and broken encoding declarations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:225
msgid ""
"Support for creating spiders based on pre-defined templates, to speed up "
"spider creation and make their code more consistent on large projects. See :"
"command:`genspider` command for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:229
msgid ""
"Extensible :ref:`stats collection <topics-stats>` for multiple spider "
"metrics, useful for monitoring the performance of your spiders and detecting "
"when they get broken"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:233
msgid ""
"An :ref:`Interactive shell console <topics-shell>` for trying XPaths, very "
"useful for writing and debugging your spiders"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:236
msgid ""
"A :ref:`System service <topics-scrapyd>` designed to ease the deployment and "
"run of your spiders in production."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:239
msgid ""
"A built-in :ref:`Web service <topics-webservice>` for monitoring and "
"controlling your bot"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:242
msgid ""
"A :ref:`Telnet console <topics-telnetconsole>` for hooking into a Python "
"console running inside your Scrapy process, to introspect and debug your "
"crawler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:246
msgid ""
":ref:`Logging <topics-logging>` facility that you can hook on to for "
"catching errors during the scraping process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:249
msgid "Support for crawling based on URLs discovered through `Sitemaps`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:251
msgid "A caching DNS resolver"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:254
msgid "What's next?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/overview.rst:256
msgid ""
"The next obvious steps are for you to `download Scrapy`_, read :ref:`the "
"tutorial <intro-tutorial>` and join `the community`_. Thanks for your "
"interest!"
msgstr ""
